Indistinguishability Obfuscation
Program obfuscation
It aims to make computer programs unintelligible while preserving
their functionality.
Indistinguishability Obfuscation
Virtual black-box obfuscation
It asks that an obfuscated program be no more useful than a black
box implementing the program.
Indistinguishability obfuscation
It asks only that obfuscation of any two distinct (equal-size)
programs that implement identical functionalities be
computationally indistinguishable from each other.
So we introduce a new technique for applying indistinguishability
obfuscation, that we call punctured programs.
Punctured Program
Idea
Alter a program by surgically removing a key element of the
program and does not alter the functionality of the program.
Punctured Program
Example
Transforming a natural private-key encryption scheme into a public-
key encryption scheme.
Secret key is PRF(K,r);
Outputs (r,PRF(K,r)+m);
Punctured Program
Example
We make a public key encryption function which is functionally
equal to the original private key encryption function.
punctured function
original function
Even if the adversary knew this punctured PRF secret key, it would
not be able to break the security of the challenge ciphertext.
Punctured Program
Example
The second step is replacing the obfuscation of the original function
with the obfuscation of the punctured function.
The idea is to find a way to move the puncturing to a location that
is never functionally accessed by the program.
PRG(pseudo-random generator) that maps bits to 2 bits, where
is a security parameter.
Deniable Encryption
Definition & Background
A public key used for encryption
Sender was forced to reveal message and the randomness
Purpose: Provide a faking algorithm (allow to produce fake
randomness for any message chosen by anyone)
Indistinguishable from the true randomness to any adversary (that
does not possess the secret decryption key)
Deniable Encryption
Construction
The public key consists of two obfuscated programs.
1. an obfuscation of an Encryption algorithm
2. an obfuscation of an Explain algorithm
Deniable Encryption
Encryption algorithm
Input: a message m and a long random string u
Instead of direct encryption, it first checks for a special hidden
sparse trigger
checks if the randomness u is itself an encoding of some valid
cipher text c and the message m
If so, it outputs this cipher text c hidden in the encoding (fake
randomness has some relationship with m and c)
Otherwise, it uses u to encrypt m to produce a cipher text c under a
standard encryption E(PKE)
Deniable Encryption
Encryption algorithm (continue)
When coins u chosen truly at random, it will almost always correctly
encrypt m, since the hidden sparse triggers form a negligible
fraction of possible u values.
The randomness needs to be long enough (be hidden in sparse
space)
Deniable Encryption
Explain algorithm
Input: a cipher text c, a message m and some randomness
outputs an encoding of (c;m). (fake randomness)
fake randomness can explain any cipher text as any desired
message.
Deniable Encryption
Explain algorithm (continue)
fake randomness serves as a hidden trigger for the Encrypt
program
if Encrypt program discovers this hidden trigger, it is to immediately
output the cipher text c that is hidden in the encoding (not output a
correct cipher text)
Deniable Encryption
Improvement
Explain will need to produce pseudorandom encodings, so that the
adversary cannot immediately distinguish fake randomness from
true one.
For example, if the adversary can take a fake randomness uX, and
modify it slightly so that it still encodes the same cipher text
message pair (cX;mX), then the adversary would learn that the
sender is faking.
Deniable Encryption
Improvement (continue)
Solution: make use of the punctured programs technique with
multiple PRFs that have been enhanced to have additional
properties
